Data was exacted from 69 studies. The median sample size is 38, ranging from 8 to 470 subjects.

Meta-analysis

#Subset larger studies >N in each group
minSamp=20
sampleBig <- subset(samplesize,nA>minSamp & nB>minSamp & Exclude==0)

#Run meta-analysis
m.publ=metabin(Apos, nA, Bpos, nB, data=sampleBig, studlab=paste0(First_Author, " (", Year, ")"), method.tau = "PM", sm="OR")
or=exp(m.publ$TE.random)
forest(m.publ, sortvar=Year, prediction=TRUE, label.right = "Favors Positive", label.left = "Favors Negative")

I first performed a meta-analysis of 11 studies which had more than 20 subjects in each group. 2 studies were excluded because their data were subsets of later larger studies.

The pooled odds-ratio from the meta-analysis, assuming a random effects model, was 2.28.

Clinically meaningful effect size

I computed a weighted average of the probability of seizure freedom in the negative finding group, which was 0.562. That is equivalent to odds for the negative group of 1.28, which can be multiplied by the pooled odds ratio of 2.28 to give the odds of the positive group of 2.93, or probability of seizure freedom of 0.745. Thus we define our clinically meaningful effect size as 56.2% seizure free in the negative group and 74.5% seizure free in the positive group.

Calculate power

I will compute the power for each study using the number of subjects in the positive group and number of subjects in the negative group, using the R package Exact and the Chi-square statistical test.

powerVal <-rep(0,numStudies)
for (i in 1:numStudies) {
  temp <-power.exact.test(pPos,pNeg,samplesize$nA[i],samplesize$nB[i],method="pearson chisq")
  powerVal[i] <- temp$power
}
powerMedian <- median(powerVal)
moreThan50 = sum(powerVal>.5)

The median power is 18.4%. Only 4 of 69 studies have greater than 50% power.

Select 90th percentile

samplesize2 <- cbind(samplesize,powerVal) #add power in

sorted <- sort(powerVal,decreasing=TRUE,index.return=TRUE) #sort from high power to low

Power vs.Sample Size plot

I will calculate the power for a range of sample sizes, assuming 2:1 allocation

#Create data for plot
nMax <- 100
n1 <-c(1:nMax)
n2 <- 2*n1
nTot <- n1+n2

powerSampleSize <-rep(0,nMax)
for (i in 1:nMax) {
  temp <-power.exact.test(pPos,pNeg,n2[i],n1[i],method="pearson chisq")
  powerSampleSize[i] <- temp$power
}

Plotting code is hidden but included in the Rmd file

Figure 1: Power as a function of sample size. Assuming 2:1 allocation, a study would need 231 subjects (154 vs.77) to have 80% statistical power to detect a difference in seizure freedom of 74.5%in group 1 and 56.2% in group 2. However, the median SEEG study only has around 18% power to detect this difference. For 2:1 allocation, this corresponds to a sample size of 27 (18 vs.9).

The exact power calculation does not increase monotonically with increasing sample size. This is likely because the Chi-square test relies on a Gaussian approximation which doesnt apply for small sample sizes, and for some values the percentages fall in between the discrete bins.
